'''[[Moscow University]] Herbarium''' ('''MW''') is the second largest [[herbarium]] in [[Russia]] after the [[Komarov Institute]] (LE).{{fact|date=October 2017}}

The herbarium is focused on the flora of temperate [[Eurasia]] with an emphasis on the flora of Russia.{{fact|date=October 2017}} The collections of MW include 1,030,669 specimens (incl. ca. 5K type specimens) [http://sweetgum.nybg.org/science/ih/herbarium_details.php?irn=125298] (62nd place in the world's ranking) representing 37,100 species and subspecies of vascular plants and 2,223 species and subspecies of bryophytes. MW holds some important historical collections by G.F. Hoffmann, J.F. Ehrhart, C.B. Trinius, J.R. and J.G.A. Forsters, etc.{{fact|date=October 2017}}

The Moscow University Herbarium added a millionth specimen to the collections in June 2016.{{fact|date=October 2017}} An average annual growth of the collection in 2005–2016 was 15,100 specimens, with an exceptional 22,013 specimens added to the herbarium in 2016.{{fact|date=October 2017}} Since 2005, major accessions originated from [[Eastern Europe]], [[Siberia]] and [[Russian Far East]], the [[Caucasus]], and [[South Asia]] (vascular plants); [[Taymyr Peninsula|Taimyr]], Russian Far East, and North Caucasus (bryophytes).

The Moscow University Herbarium has gained budget for the digitisation of collections within the Program of the National Depository Bank of Live Systems, and around 911,000 specimens (89%) were scanned since May 2015. All these records are published already online,<ref>{{cite web| url=http://plant.depo.msu.ru/ | title=Национальный банк-депозитарий живых систем | website=plant.depo.msu.ru | publisher=[[Moscow State University]] | accessdate=15 October 2017 }}</ref> including JPG images and metadata required for indexing. <ref>{{cite| url=https://elibrary.ru/item.asp?id=29008518 | title=ГЕРБАРИЙ МОСКОВСКОГО УНИВЕРСИТЕТА (MW) СЕГОДНЯ: ФОНДЫ, ОНЛАЙН ДОСТУП И НАУЧНАЯ РАБОТА | website=elibrary.ru | accessdate=15 October 2017 }}</ref>

Currently, the Moscow Digital Herbarium holds the largest digitised herbarium collections from Russia, Ukraine, Mongolia, Georgia, Abkhazia, South Ossetia, Azerbaijan, Belarus, Moldova, Latvia, as well as from Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Uzbekistan, Turkmenistan, and Tajikistan. Also, Moscow Digital Herbarium is the second largest hub of digitised herbarium collections from Armenia, Lithuania, North Korea, Mali and the third largest for Cyprus and Vietnam [https://www.gbif.org/dataset/902c8fe7-8f38-45b0-854e-c324fed36303].

