{{Infobox U.S. Courts of Appeals case |Litigants=United States v. Gementera |Court=[[United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit]] |CourtSeal= |ArgueDate=May 11, |ArgueYear=2004 |DecideDate=August 9, |DecideYear=2004 |FullName=United States v. Gementera |Citations=379 [[Federal Reporter|F.3d]] [https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/F3/379/596/475040/ 596] |Prior= |Subsequent= |Holding= |Judges=[[Diarmuid O'Scannlain]], [[Eugene E. Siler, Jr.]] ([[United States Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit|6th Cir.]]), [[Michael Daly Hawkins]] |Majority=O'Scannlain |JoinMajority=Siler |Dissent=Hawkins |LawsApplied=[[Sentencing Reform Act]]; [[Eighth Amendment to the United States Constitution|U.S. Const. amend. VIII]] }} [[Image:U.S. Post Office & Courthouse (San Francisco).jpg|thumb|300px|The U.S. Post Office and Courthouse at the corner of 7th and Mission Street in San Francisco.]] '''''United States v. Gementera''''', [[case citation|379]] [[Federal Reporter|F.3d]] 596 (9th Cir. 2004)<ref>{{cite court |litigants=United States v. Gementera |vol=379 |reporter=F.3d |opinion=596 |pinpoint= |court=9th Cir. |date=2004 |url=https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/F3/379/596/475040/ |accessdate=2017-11-03 |quote=}}</ref>, was a [[legal case|case]] decided by the [[9th Circuit]] that held that a judge had the statutory authority to impose a [[sentence (law)|sentence]] for mail theft that involved public [[reintegrative shaming]] because the punishment was reasonably related to the statutory objective of [[rehabilitation (penology)|rehabilitation]]. The punishment required that the thief wear a [[sandwich board]] sign stating, "I stole mail; this is my punishment", while standing for eight hours outside of a [[San Francisco]] postal facility.<ref>''Gementera'', 379 F.3d at 599.</ref><ref>Dressler, J. ''Understanding Criminal Law, Fifth Edition.'' [[Matthew Bender|Matthew Bender & Company, Inc.]] Newark, NJ: 2009, p. 24</ref>
